LaserWriter Bridge 2.0.1 Userﾕs GuideRevision AOverviewThe LaserWriter Bridge 2.0.1 allows you to use a LocalTalk-based LaserWriter printer while simultaneously using an Ethernet or Token Ring network.  This offers you a simple and effective way to gradually upgrade your LocalTalk-based Macintosh computers to a higher performance network while preserving your investment in a LocalTalk-only LaserWriter. You can take advantage of high-speed Ethernet or Token Ring networks for your data transfer needs and use a LocalTalk LaserWriter for cost-effective printing.The LaserWriter Bridge operates by setting up a secondary network connection on LocalTalk after you have selected your primary network connection as either Ethernet or Token Ring. Typically, printer data and control information is passed from the primary network onto the secondary network connection, LocalTalk, and then on to your printer.The LaserWriter Bridge 2.0.1 supports up to 32 LocalTalk-based LaserWriter printers on its LocalTalk network although a practical maximum is 8 printers. Only one LaserWriter Bridge may be operational on a single LocalTalk network segment. You may have many LaserWriter Bridges attached to your primary network (Ethernet or Token Ring), however.Once the LaserWriter Bridge is active on a LocalTalk network segment, all other Macintoshes (desktops, portables or Newtons) directly attached to that LocalTalk segment will only be able to use the LaserWriter(s) located on that LocalTalk network segment. Also, those Macintoshes on LocalTalk will not be able to use AppleShare (or file sharing) among themselves.If full access is required for all devices on the LocalTalk network, you should use the Apple LocalTalk Bridge software (Apple Part Number M3246Z/A) which fully bridges both primary and secondary networks allowing all users to share all resources.This version of the LaserWriter Bridge is not compatible with Open Transport-based Macintoshes. The Installer will not install the bridge on a system with Open Transport and if the bridge is launched on such a system, the bridge will automatically terminate operation. Look for a new version of the bridge to support Open Transport-based Macintoshes.System Requirements･	A Macintosh CPU with at least a 68020 processor･	70K of free RAM･	System 7 or later･	AppleTalk version 58 or later (included with the bridge installer disk)･	An Ethernet card or a Token Ring card or an Ethernet transceiver (for computers with built-in Ethernet) and cable･	A LocalTalk connector and cable･	A LocalTalk-based LaserWriter printer plugged into the Macintoshﾕs printer port using LocalTalk cabling･ No Apple Internet Router software may be installed on the same Macintosh as the LaserWriter BridgeInstallation and set upThe LaserWriter Bridge 2.0.1 is installed by running the Installer program on the Network Software Installer disk version 1.5.1. It is strongly recommended that an Easy Install be performed before installing the bridge so that all network resources are updated.1. Insert the Network Software Installer disk in your Macintosh and double-click the diskﾕs    icon to open it.2. Open the Installer program, review the Welcome screen, and click OK.3. Make sure that the disk indicated in the ﾒDestination Diskﾓ dialog box is your current    startup disk, and use the ﾒEasy Installﾓ installer option.4.	Click the ﾒInstallﾓ button.5. When you see a message reporting the installation was successful, click Restart.6. After restarting, set your primary network connection.    ･ Open the Network control panel under the Control Panels menu.    ･ Click the EtherTalk (or TokenTalk) connection to select it as your primary network       connection.    ･ Click OK to confirm the change of networks.       Using the LaserWriter Bridge, LocalTalk becomes your secondary network connection.7. Reinsert the Network Software Installer disk in your Macintosh and double-click the    diskﾕs icon to open it.8. Open the Installer program, review the Welcome screen, and click OK.9. Make sure that the disk indicated in the ﾒDestination Diskﾓ dialog box is your current    startup disk, and select the ﾒCustom Installﾓ option located under the ﾒEasy Installﾓ    button at the upper left. Select Custom Install by clicking and holding on the ﾒEasy    Installﾓ button then moving the mouse until the Custom Install option is highlighted.10. Scroll through the Custom Install items to find the ﾒLaserWriter Bridgeﾓ and click     on its checkbox to select it for installation.11.	Click the ﾒInstallﾓ button.12. When you see a message reporting the installation was successful, click Restart.After restart, the LaserWriter Bridge will be On and network access is set to Public. It may take up to one minute for the bridge to start up.On/Off ControlAfter installation, the default setting for the Bridge is On.  To change this, double-click on the LaserWriter Bridge control panel and click the ﾒOffﾓ radio button. Closing the Bridge control panel will immediately turn off your bridge and terminate the connection between the two networks.  Clicking the ﾒOnﾓ button again and closing the Bridge control panel will start up the bridge and reestablish the connection between the two networks. Allow up to one minute for the bridge to start up. Once the bridge is loaded (at startup), you can turn off and turn on the bridge without having to restart. You may also switch between private and public network access at any time. If you shut down the Macintosh with the bridge set to ﾒOffﾓ, the bridge will not load when you restart the computer.  If you shut down the Macintosh with the bridge set to ﾒOnﾓ, the bridge will be loaded when you restart the computer and will set up the connection between both primary and secondary networks.Switching your network connectionSwitching your primary network connection in the Network control panel (say from EtherTalk to LocalTalk) while the bridge is running will disable the bridge. Switching back to EtherTalk (or TokenTalk) as your primary network connection will require a restart of the Macintosh to start up the bridge.Network AccessPrivate If network access is set to Private, only the Macintosh functioning as the bridge will be able to print to the LaserWriter(s) on the LocalTalk network. This makes the LaserWriter a private printer. Users on the primary network will not be able to print to the LaserWriter(s).PublicIf network access is set to Public, all users on the Ethernet or Token Ring network, including the Macintosh functioning as the bridge, will be able to print to the LaserWriter(s) on the LocalTalk network.CompatibilityThe LaserWriter Bridge is compatible with AppleShare 4.0 or later, Apple Internet Router 3.0.1, Apple Remote Access 2.0 and all versions of System 7.  Although the LaserWriter Bridge will work on Ethernet or Token Ring networks that already have a Apple Internet Router running on it, it is not possible to run LaserWriter Bridge on the same Macintosh that is running the Apple Internet Router. The LaserWriter Bridge will not start up if any AppleTalk router is attached to the same LocalTalk network. Nor will the bridge start up when launched on a system using Open Transport.TroubleshootingThere are several errors you may encounter that interfere with the operation of the LaserWriter Bridge. The error messages you may encounter and their solutions are listed below.LaserWriter Bridge cannot start because AppleTalk is not active. Please use the Chooser to activate AppleTalk, then restart the Macintosh.AppleTalk must be active on the Macintosh for the bridge to operate. Open the Chooser and click the AppleTalk Active button.Making AppleTalk inactive or switching network connections has stopped LaserWriter Bridge services.Turning off AppleTalk or switching your primary network connection in the Network control panel will disable the LaserWriter Bridge. You will need to restart the Macintosh to activate the bridge after reactivating AppleTalk or reselecting your primary network connection (EtherTalk or TokenTalk).LaserWriter Bridge cannot continue because of a network number conflict. Please restart the Macintosh.The primary network connection (Ethernet or Token Ring) can have one or more active routers and additional routers might become active on the network after the LaserWriter Bridge is activated. When the network administrator sets up a router, they must specify a range of valid network numbers (or addresses). When a Macintosh is started, it attempts to acquire a network number within this range.A Macintoshﾕs network number cannot change after startup so if a router subsequently appears, the Macintoshﾕs network number may fall outside the routerﾕs valid network numbers. The LaserWriter Bridge is designed to terminate operation if this is detected. In order for network services to return, restart the Macintosh so it can acquire a valid network number.LaserWriter Bridge cannot start because of an AppleTalk error.AppleTalk errors are quite rare, but may be caused by file or resource corruption in the System file. If an AppleTalk error occurs, the LaserWriter Bridge ceases to operate. Try reinstalling the AppleTalk and LaserWriter Bridge software using the Network Software Installer. You may also see this error if you try to launch the bridge on a system that is using Open Transport. Look for a new version of the LaserWriter Bridge to support Open Transport.LaserWriter Bridge cannot start because the printer port is in use. Please select another AppleTalk connection in the Network control panel, then try again.For the LaserWriter Bridge to operate you must use a different network as your primary network connection, such as EtherTalk or TokenTalk. LocalTalk becomes your secondary network connection. Open the Network control panel and select another network connection (see step 6 above).LaserWriter Bridge could not obtain a LocalTalk address because all addresses are in use by other network devices. Please contact your network administrator.This message indicates a ﾒNo Free MultiNode Addressﾓ error. In order for the LaserWriter Bridge to transfer data between LocalTalk and another network, the Macintosh must obtain a pseudo address for sending data to and from devices on both networks. If a pseudo address cannot be acquired, the LaserWriter Bridge will cease to operate.Users that also use routers must insure that enough node addresses are allocated to network segments that include users of the LaserWriter Bridge. Network node addresses must be greater than the sum of the number of Macintosh users and printers and any other devices on both network segments (which include the LaserWriters on the bridged Macintoshes). The easiest way to do this is to allocate a larger network range for each network segment (such as an EtherTalk segment with users running the LaserWriter Bridge) when configuring your router.LaserWriter Bridge requires AppleTalk version 58 or later. Please install AppleTalk version 58 or later, then try again.The LaserWriter Bridge requires AppleTalk version 58 to operate. It is available on the Network Software Installer where the LaserWriter Bridge is found. Be sure to install AppleTalk version 58 when installing the LaserWriter Bridge.LaserWriter Bridge was unable to start because of an unspecified error.Under some circumstances, the LaserWriter Bridge may encounter a Macintosh operating system error during startup. Try restarting to clear the error or look at other extensions (INITs) that load during startup for a possible conflict. Restart the Macintosh to retry.Macintosh Printer Port Already in Use.This error message occurs if the Macintoshﾕs printer port is already in use by another program when the LaserWriter Bridge is starting up. The bridge is disabled if this condition is detected.The LaserWriter Bridge routes printer data packets from your primary network connection to the Macintoshﾕs LocalTalk port. Because the printer port is always one of the two networks, the LocalTalk port cannot already be in use when the LaserWriter Bridge is activated. During startup, there are four ways in which the printer port can be in use:･ You set the current AppleTalk port to LocalTalk in the Network control panel. Set your primary network connection in the Network control panel.･ You forget to select the primary network connection in the Network control panel so the bridge defaults to the built-in LocalTalk port. Set your primary network connection in the Network control panel.･ You selected a network other than then LocalTalk network in the Network control panel but an error occurs while switching to the selected network and the default LocalTalk port is used instead. Recheck your network cabling for Ethernet or Token Ring and set your primary network connection in the Network control panel.･ You installed a software product (such as a terminal program) which reserves the printer (or serial) port before the LaserWriter Bridge is activated and therefore the port is already in use. You must quit the other program and restart the Macintosh to clear the use of the port.There is a router or a Macintosh running LaserWriter Bridge software on this LocalTalk network. LaserWriter Bridge cannot run on a LocalTalk network that has a router or another LaserWriter Bridge.You can only use the LaserWriter Bridge on a LocalTalk segment that does not already have an active AppleTalk Internet Router, LocalTalk Bridge or another LaserWriter Bridge. If the bridge detects another Router or bridge on the same LocalTalk segment, the LaserWriter Bridge will not start up. Remove one of the bridges or router(s).If the LaserWriter Bridge software detects the presence of the Apple Internet Router software installed on the same Macintosh as the bridge, the bridge software will display this message and not start up. Remove either the bridge or router software or use a different Macintosh.There is not enough memory available to start the LaserWriter Bridge.The LaserWriter Bridge requires approximately 70K of RAM to run. If during startup the bridge is unable to allocate enough memory space, the LaserWriter Bridge cannot run. Add more RAM to the Macintosh or quit a program (usually another extension or INIT) to allow more memory to be allocated.For more information about the Apple LaserWriter Bridge, ordering the Apple LocalTalk Bridge (M3246Z/A) or other networking products, contact the Apple Network Information Line at (408) 862-3385, or through AppleLink at ABS.NETINFO.ｩ 1995 Apple Computer, Inc. Apple, Macintosh, Newton, AppleTalk, EtherTalk, LocalTalk, LaserWriter and TokenTalk are trademarks of Apple Computer, Inc., registered in the U.S.A. and other countries.